### 1. LOGIN (Execute this first!)
# The JWT is returned as a Cookie. IntelliJ's HTTP Client will automatically
# save the Cookie and use it for all the subsequent requests below!
POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/auth/login
Content-Type: application/json
Accept: application/json

{
  "email": "j.borkowski@student.pb.edu.pl",
  "password": "admin123"
}

###

### 2. Fetch all requests for the currently logged in user
# You can append ?status=DRAFT to filter by status
GET http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests
Accept: application/json

###

### 3. Fetch a single request by its UUID
# (Replace the UUID with one you get from the GET /requests response)
GET http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests/req_AZ647sK5eZa56BQUKJVGYA
Accept: application/json

###

### 4. Example of an ERROR - Request Not Found
# This will trigger the RequestNotFoundException.
# You will see the "Cost Category not found." (or Request) message, 
# AND you will see the traceId injected into the JSON response!
GET http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests/ffffffff-ffff-ffff-ffff-ffffffffffff
Accept: application/json

###

### 5. Create a new Request
POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests
Content-Type: application/json
Accept: application/json

{
  "title": "New Laptop for Development",
  "description": "Need a new MacBook Pro for the new backend developer.",
  "amount": 12500.00,
  "departmentId": 1,
  "costCategoryId": 1,
  "fundingSourceId": 1
}

###

### 6. Example of a Validation ERROR
# The amount is negative, which will trigger Jakarta validation errors.
POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests
Content-Type: application/json
Accept: application/json

{
  "title": "Invalid Request",
  "description": "This request has a negative amount.",
  "amount": -50.00,
  "departmentId": 1,
  "costCategoryId": 1,
  "fundingSourceId": 1
}

###

### 7. Add a Comment to a Request
POST http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests/req_AZ647sK5eZa56BQUKJVGYA/comments
Content-Type: application/json
Accept: application/json

{
  "content": "Can we please expedite this? The new developer starts on Monday."
}

###

### 8. Fetch Comments for a Request
GET http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests/req_AZ647sK5eZa56BQUKJVGYA/comments
Accept: application/json

###

### 9. Delete a Request
# NOTE: Depending on your business rules, you may only be able to delete DRAFT requests,
# or only Admins can delete requests. Give it a try!
DELETE http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests/req_AZ647sK5eZa56BQUKJVGYA
Accept: application/json

###

### 10. Change Request Status
# Changes the status of a request (e.g., from DRAFT to PENDING, or PENDING to APPROVED).
# The description is optional but good for audit logs!
PATCH http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests/req_AZ647sK5eZa56BQUKJVGYA/status
Content-Type: application/json
Accept: application/json

{
  "status": "SUBMITTED",
  "description": "Ready for Dean's Office review."
}

###

### 11. Fetch Request History (Audit Log)
# See the full timeline of status changes, edits, and creation.
GET http://localhost:8080/api/v1/requests/req_AZ647sK5eZa56BQUKJVGYA/history
Accept: application/json